Radiation therapy, such as external beam radiation, works by damaging the DNA of cancer cells, making it difficult for them to divide and grow. One of the primary mechanisms by which radiation induces DNA damage is by causing breaks in double-stranded DNA. This occurs when high-energy radiation, such as X-rays or gamma rays, interacts with the DNA molecule, leading to the formation of free radicals that can break the phosphodiester backbone of the DNA. As a result, the DNA is unable to replicate and the cell is unable to divide, ultimately leading to cell death.

